{{Essay-like|date=February 2016}} '''The Brazilian packaging market''' is the fifth-largest in the world, having realized US$35 billion (1.5% of GDP) in sales in 2014, with Brazil being the [[List of countries by GDP (nominal)|seventh largest economy]] in the world by nominal GDP.<ref name=":2">{{Cite book|title = Brasil PackTrends 2020|last = Sarantópoulos|first = Claire I. G. L.|publisher = ITAL - Instituto de Tecnologia de Alimentos|year = 2012|isbn = 978-85-7029-119-6|location = Campinas - SP|pages = 10|editor-last = Amaral Rego|editor-first = Raul|display-authors=etal}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.datamark.com.br/en/general-data/|title = Datamark - Market Intelligence Brazil|date = |accessdate = 2015-12-11|website = |publisher = }}</ref> The [[Packaging and labeling|packaging]] market includes manufacturing of packaging materials from raw materials, distribution of packaging materials to producers, packaging design as well as recycling processes. The packaging sector has strong ties to environmental organizations and tries to adapt to the demands of environmentally friendly production. As a result of this development, [[Sustainable packaging]] emerged as a promising future market for innovation.<ref>{{Cite journal|url = http://www.packagingdigest.com/sustainable-packaging/why-the-2030-sustainable-development-goals-matter-to-packaging-professionals1512|title = Why the 2030 Sustainable Development Goals matter to packaging professionals|last = Han|first = Rosemary|date = 2015-12-01|journal = Packaging Digest|doi = |pmid = |access-date = 2015-12-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url = https://www.nytimes.com/2014/11/20/business/energy-environment/packaging-environment.html|title = The Side Effects of Consumerism. Large Producers and Retailers Cutting Back on Packaging|last = Gardiner|first = Beth|date = 2014-11-19|work = |access-date = 2015-12-02|via = |newspaper = The New York Times}}</ref>
== Market development == For the period between 2011 and 2016, Brazil shows an estimated median growth of 6.2%, realizing a sales value of US$34 billion in 2016, leaving behind Canada and being on a level with France.<ref name=":2" /> The constant growth of the Brazilian packaging market is not a unique phenomenon. The global packaging market is on the rise, which is due to a combination of various factors like the growing urbanization, investments in the construction sector and the expansion of the health sector.<ref name=":3">{{Cite book|title = Brasil PackTrends 2020|last = Sarantópoulos|publisher = ITAL|year = 2012|pages = 9|display-authors=etal}}</ref> The demand for environmentally friendly packaging types has also been increasing steadily since the 2000s and the resulting growth from innovation contributes to this trend. Additionally, the rapid growth of the so-called [[BRIC|BRIC states]] over the course of the 2000s as well as the early post-[[Financial crisis of 2007–08|crisis]] period plays a major role in the growth trend of the global packaging market.<ref name=":3" /> Despite the 2015 economic slowdowns - especially in China and Brazil<ref>{{Cite news|url = https://www.reuters.com/article/2015/11/27/us-brazil-economy-gdp-idUSKBN0TG1HK20151127|title = Brazil's economy tailspin seen at record speed in third quarter|last = Cascione|first = Silvio|date = 2015-11-27|work = Reuters|access-date = 2015-12-02|via = }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.frbsf.org/economic-research/publications/economic-letter/2015/november/global-fallout-from-china-industrial-slowdown/|title = Global Fallout from China's Industrial Slowdown|date = 2015-11-23|accessdate = 2015-12-02|website = |publisher = Federal Reserve Bank of San Francisco|last = Spiegel|first = Mark}}</ref> - the highest growth rates for the 2011-2016 period can be observed in these states, with China, India, '''Brazil''' and Russia showing growth rates of 7.9%, 7.7%, '''6.2%''' and 4.9%, respectively.<ref name=":2" /> The high growth rates in these countries can be explained by rising personal incomes, resulting in higher demand for a broad product range, which in turn creates growth for the packaging producers of these respective products.<ref name=":2" /> Despite its good CAGR, it was projected that due to the [[Economic history of Brazil#2010s economic contraction|Brazilian recession]] the 2014 sales equaling US$35 billion would have decreased by 2.9% in 2016, to reach US$34 billion.<ref>{{Cite book|title = Brasil PackTrends 2020|last = Sarantópoulos|publisher = |year = 2012|isbn = |location = |pages = 10|display-authors=etal}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url = http://economia.estadao.com.br/noticias/geral,13-sintomas-de-que-a-economia-brasileira-esta-em-recessao,1551533|title = 13 sintomas de que a economia brasileira está em recessão|last = Scholz|first = Cley|date = 2014-08-29|work = O Estado de S. Paulo (Estadão)|access-date = 2015-12-11|via = }}</ref> {| class="wikitable sortable" |+Packaging sales per country per year (Source: Brasil PackTrends 2020 (2012)) !Countries !Sales 2008 (billion US$) !Ranking 2008 !Sales 2011 (billion US$) !Ranking 2011 !Sales 2016 (billion US$) !Ranking 2016 |- |US | align="center"|129 | align="center"|1 | align="center"|141 | align="center"|1 | align="center"|164 | align="center"|1 |- |China | align="center"|50 | align="center"|2 | align="center"|80 | align="center"|2 | align="center"|117 | align="center"|2 |- |Japan | align="center"|70 | align="center"|3 | align="center"|76 | align="center"|3 | align="center"|87 | align="center"|3 |- |Germany | align="center"|33 | align="center"|4 | align="center"|37 | align="center"|4 | align="center"|42 | align="center"|4 |- |France | align="center"|27 | align="center"|5 | align="center"|30 | align="center"|6 | align="center"|34 | align="center"|5 |- |Canada | align="center"|24 | align="center"|7 | align="center"|27 | align="center"|7 | align="center"|30 | align="center"|7 |- | style="background: ye