== Packaging trends == An analysis of the Brazilian packaging market unveils a set of products, the popularity of which has steadily been increasing since the late 2000s. Additionally to that, there are some general tendencies that are steering the market.
=== General trends === [[File:The five main trends in the packaging industry.png|alt=The image provides a visual representation the five main trends in the packaging industry as well as the characteristics of packaging according to these trends, as is being mentioned in the article.|thumb|The five main trends in the packaging industry. Image in modified form according to Brasil PackTrends 2020 (2012).|390x390px]] In its study "Brasil PackTrends 2020" (2012), the [[:pt:Instituto de Tecnologia de Alimentos|Brazilian Institute for Food Technology (ITAL)]] identified five general trends in the packaging industry: 1) convenience and simplicity, 2) esthetics and identity, 3) quality and new technologies, 4) sustainability and ethics, and 5) safety and regulatory issues.<ref>{{Cite book|title = Brasil PackTrends 2020|last = Sarantópoulos|publisher = ITAL|year = 2012|isbn = |location = |pages = 72–73|display-authors=etal}}</ref> Despite delivering examples from the Brazilian market, these five tendencies are not taylor-made for Brazil, as they - to large parts - also apply to the [[packaging industry]] as a whole.
==== Convenience and simplicity ==== Consumers nowadays value products that facilitate their lives, that are easy to use and time-efficient. In terms of packaging, this means that a successful packaging has to be easy to open, easy to use, resealable and easily disposable. With regard to food, the popularity of packaging that enables a quick and simple preparation (e.g. in the microwave) also keeps rising. Packaging has to refrain from posing any unnecessary obstacle whatsoever, this also includes language design, that is, packaging ought to use an easy languages and simple graphics while not overloading the consumer with information. Additionally to that, packaging has to adapt to socio-economic changes. As urbanization is increasing and single-person household become more and more common, producers have to provide food packaging with individual portions or packaging that, for instance, allows a quick and easy preparation of meals in the microwave.<ref>{{Cite book|title = Brasil PackTrends 2020|last = Sarantópoulos|publisher = ITAL|year = 2012|isbn = |location = |pages = 70–71, 74|display-authors=etal}}</ref>
==== Aesthetics and identity ==== When heading for a product, consumers (in)directly seek objective as well as subjective satisfaction. Adequate packaging can increase the consumer's feeling of identification with a product by, e.g., promoting a certain life-style or by conveying high quality, enhancing the product's ability of serving as a status symbol. Another important consumer type is the one that values health and a high quality of life above everything else. The proportion of packaging that promotes health benefits of the product and that conveys to the customer a certain feeling of doing something good for their health is steadily increasing. Another trend involves packaging that turns products into collectibles and make the packaging more valuable to the customer than the actual product itself.<ref>{{Cite book|title = Brasil PackTrends 2020|last = Sarantópoulos|publisher = ITAL|year = 2012|isbn = |location = |pages = 75|display-authors=etal}}</ref> A good example of this trend is the [[Share a Coke]] marketing campaign by [[The Coca-Cola Company|Coca-Cola]], that was launched in Brazil in 2015, four years after the first campaign was launched in Australia.<ref>{{Cite journal|url = http://www.marketingmagazine.co.uk/article/1372962/share-coke-mad-men-campaigns-defined-coke-wendy-clark|title = From Share a Coke to Mad Men: the campaigns that defined Coke under Wendy Clark|last = Spary|first = Sara|date = 2015-11-17|journal = Marketing Magazine|doi = |pmid = |access-date = 2015-12-02}}</ref> Colors transmit esthetics, yet post 2010 developments in the Brazilian packaging market show a rising preference of simple styles by customers.
==== Quality and new technologies ==== The packaging sector provides opportunities for new technologies as well as new types of materials that improve a product's lifespan and [[Food microbiology|microbiological safety]]. Active and intelligent packaging can, for instance, absorb [[oxygen]] and [[Carbon dioxide|CO2]], or even heat itself. Others provide the consumer with indicators on temperature, freshness or the degree of ripeness. Advancements have also been made on the nano level. Packaging that avails itself of nanotechnology can create barriers to gases, humidity or UV radiation. New technology also helps at making the product weigh less. Increasingly, [[biopolymer]]s are used as the material basis for packaging, replacing fossil-based polymers. Yet, new packaging types tend to face issues like a higher price and hence, difficulties in competition with the cheaper fossil-based materials.<ref>{{Cite book|title = Brasil PackTrends 2020|last = Sarantópoulos|publisher = ITAL|year = 2012|isbn = |location = |pages = 76–78|display-authors=etal}}</ref>
==== Sustainability and ethics ==== With environmental issues like [[climate change]] becoming more and more of a priority challenge, the packaging market has adapted to new consumer demands like applying sustainable packaging and keeping the [[carbon footprint]] low. [[Life-cycle assessment|Life cycle assessments]] and [[Life Cycle Thinking|Life-cycle thinking]] in general are regarded as the best instruments to calculate the environmental costs of a product or service. Sustainability is not only achieved by using 100% renewable materials, but also by, for instance, making packaging smaller so that more units of the product can be shipped at a time, which in turn reduces the collective carbon footprint. Making the transition to sustainable packaging also creates an incentive for the customer to identify with the product, as the product will convey environmental consciousness. With regard to that, it's important to mention the rising use of recycled material for packaging. Given an increased amount of recycled material, functioning [[waste management]] and [[reverse logistics]] are indispensable and promise to be an auspicious market for innovative products and services. In order to avoid obvious [[Greenwashing]], producers have been anxious to achieve quality certification from renowned environmental certification institutes like the [[Carbon Trust]] and the [[Forest Stewardship Council]].<ref>{{Cite book|title = Brasil PackTrends 2020|last = Sarantópoulos|publisher = ITAL|year = 2012|isbn = |location = |pages = 79–80|display-authors=etal}}</ref>
==== Safety and regulatory issues ==== Packaging is crucial to ensure a product's safety, quality and reliability. Packaging carries all the information the consumer may consider to be important, e.g., preparation instructions, nutritional value, date of manufacture and expiration date and producer information. The transfer of chemical contaminants from [[food contact materials]] to food is regarded as being a major issue in health studies. Hence, mathematical modelling and in-depth analyses are used in order to make estimations about the degree of this so-called [http://www.foodpackagingforum.org/food-packaging-health/migration migration] of contaminants. Packaging materials have to comply with the vast regulatory framework that has been created by lawmakers.<ref>{{Cite book|title = Brasil PackTrends 2020|last = Sarantópoulos|publisher = ITAL|year = 2012|isbn = |location = |pages = 80–82|display-authors=etal}}</ref> In 2000, four years after having had adopted the [[Mercosur|Mercosur's]] regulations managing the use of food contact materials, Brazil exempted all FCM from Mercosur's registration requirements except for FCM made from recycled materials.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|title = Keller Heckman Packaging Site -Food Packaging Regulations in Latin America: Moving Towards Harmonization|url = http://www.packaginglaw.com/3692_.shtml|website = www.packaginglaw.com|accessdate = 2015-11-30|last = Clark|first = Mitzi Ng|date = April 2014}}</ref> Despite being exempted from Mercosur's registration policy, FCM that is imported into the Brazilian market still needs to comply with all technical resolutions and Brazilian legislation incorporating the Mercsosur resolutions. Additionally to that, the Brazilian [[National Health Surveillance Agency]] (ANVISA) must be informed about any imports of FCM whatsoever.<ref name=":0" /> Laws are constantly being revised in order to match newly acquired scientific and technological insights and steadily evolving products. Along with Mercosur, the [[Food and Drug Administration|United States Food and Drug Administration]] (FDA) as well as the [[European Union]] - which passed [[Harmonization of law|harmonized legislation]] on FCM in 2004<ref>{{Cite web|title = Regulation (EC) No 1935/2004|url = http://ec.europa.eu/food/safety/chemical_safety/food_contact_materials/legislation/index_en.htm|website = ec.europa.eu|accessdate = 2015-11-30}}</ref> - ANVISA promotes globally harmonized policies and [[International regime|regimes]] for the governing of FCM.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Legislation - European Commission|url = http://ec.europa.eu/food/safety/chemical_safety/food_contact_materials/legislation/index_en.htm|website = ec.europa.eu|accessdate = 2015-11-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title = International harmonization of food quality & safety standards|last = Mermelstein|first = Neil H.|publisher = |year = 2012|isbn = |location = Chicago|pages = 72–75|work = Food Technology|volume = }}</ref>
=== Products ===
==== Stand Up Pouches ==== [[File:Stand Up Pouches IMPAK.png|thumb|Various products that use Stand Up Pouch packaging (Source: IMPAK Corporation)]] Probably the most successful innovation of the 2010s thus far has been the Stand Up Pouch, which is a special kind of [[retort pouch]] that features a bottom gusset, making it able to stand upright. Stand Up Pouches are mostly used for human alimentation products, but also for pet food as well as beauty care products. In the Brazilian market, Stand Up Pouches constantly have been managing to fit into new market niches. While showing immense growth ([[CAGR]] of 6,1% in volume and 5,8% in value between 2011 and 2014), the distribution of Stand Up Pouches in Brazil yet lags behind the Chilean and the U.S. market, which is due to a lack of supply of scale of important components like resealable zippers and nylon, causing the price for the production of Stand Up Pouches to be higher than in comparable markets. Among the ten fastest growing flexibles, Stand Up Pouches rank third with regard to CAGR in volume and fourth as regards CAGR in value.<ref name=":4">{{Cite web|title = Inovação {{!}} Datamark|url = http://www.datamark.com.br/inovacao/|website = www.datamark.com.br|accessdate = 2015-12-01}}</ref> {| class="wikitable sortable" |+Volume, value and growth of common "flexibles" in the Brazilian packaging market 2011-2014 (Source: ABIEF<ref>ABIEF: Brazilian Association of the Flexible Plastics Industry http://www.abief.com.br/</ref>) !Type !Metric Tonnes 2011 !Metric Tonnes 2012 !Metric Tonnes 2013 !Metric Tonnes 2014 !CAGR Volume !Ranking Growth
Volume !US$ thousand 2011 !US$ thousand
