2013 !US$ thousand
2014 !CAGR Value !Ranking Growth Value |- |Blisters | align="center" |6.999 | align="center" |7.759 | align="center" |8.579 | align="center" |9.173 | align="center" |7,0% | align="center" |1. | align="center" |271.929 | align="center" |305.123 | align="center" |341.830 | align="center" |366.225 | align="center" |7,7% | align="center" |2. |- |Strip | align="center" |840 | align="center" |929 | align="center" |1.101 | align="center" |1.067 | align="center" |6,2% | align="center" |2. | align="center" |10.746 | align="center" |12.177 | align="center" |13.607 | align="center" |13.623 | align="center" |6,1% | align="center" |3. |- | style="background: yellow"|Stand Up Pouches | style="background: yellow" align="center"|15.459 | style="background: yellow" align="center"|16.369 | style="background: yellow" align="center"|18.494 | style="background: yellow" align="center"|19.593 | style="background: yellow" align="center"|6,1% | style="background: yellow" align="center"|3. | style="background: yellow" align="center"|193.108 | style="background: yellow" align="center"|236.363 | style="background: yellow" align="center"|315.839 | style="background: yellow" align="center"|241.691 | style="background: yellow" align="center"|5,8% | style="background: yellow" align="center"|4. |- |Sleeves | align="center" |4.284 | align="center" |4.419 | align="center" |4.743 | align="center" |5.175 | align="center" |4,8% | align="center" |4. | align="center" |30.138 | align="center" |31.335 | align="center" |33.553 | align="center" |37.221 | align="center" |5,4% | align="center" |5. |- |Seals | align="center" |72 | align="center" |69 | align="center" |82 | align="center" |87 | align="center" |4,8% | align="center" |5. | align="center" |640 | align="center" |626 | align="center" |734 | align="center" |778 | align="center" |5,0% | align="center" |6. |- |Peel-off lids | align="center" |7.085 | align="center" |7.277 | align="center" |7.667 | align="center" |8.425 | align="center" |4,4% | align="center" |6. | align="center" |182.572 | align="center" |166.033 | align="center" |174.814 | align="center" |327.081 | align="center" |15,7% | align="center" |1. |- |Composite cans | align="center" |584 | align="center" |589 | align="center" |659 | align="center" |679 | align="center" |3,8% | align="center" |7. | align="center" |39.226 | align="center" |38.929 | align="center" |43.087 | align="center" |44.200 | align="center" |3,0% | align="center" |9. |- |Covers | align="center" |1.717 | align="center" |1.737 | align="center" |2.015 | align="center" |1.993 | align="center" |3,8% | align="center" |8. | align="center" |22.288 | align="center" |22.647 | align="center" |26.080 | align="center" |26.137 | align="center" |4,1% | align="center" |7. |- |Sachets | align="center" |24.984 | align="center" |26.081 | align="center" |27.158 | align="center" |28.486 | align="center" |3,33% | align="center" |9. | align="center" |817.660 | align="center" |836.456 | align="center" |866.666 | align="center" |945.100 | align="center" |3,7% | align="center" |8. |- |Jars/tumblers | align="center" |6.804 | align="center" |7.489 | align="center" |7.462 | align="center" |7.680 | align="center" |3,08% | align="center" |10. | align="center" |131.088 | align="center" |144.551 | align="center" |142.681 | align="center" |146.666 | align="center" |2,9% | align="center" |10. |} There are two common types of processes of filling Stand Up Pouches, namely [[Vertical form fill sealing machine|vertical form fill seal]] (VFFS) and fill-seal (FS). Whereas the former uses rolls of film of the packaging material and complex machines that shape the pouch in its typical form before filling and eventually sealing it, the latter process uses pre-formed pouches as well as two separate machines for filling and sealing the pouch, respectively. Because of the trade-off of having a high initial investment but low operational costs, VFFS is more of a long-run rather than short-run option and useful for the production of large quantities. However, as the FS process is more decentralized than the VFFS process and does not rely on one extensive machine, the chance of suffering from long downtimes for maintenance is significantly lower with FS, since failures in single production processes can be fixed more easily.<ref name=":4" />
Typical products that come in Stand Up Pouch packaging are nuts, cereals, dog and cat food, liquid soap and smaller quantities of laundry detergents.
==== Bio-based packaging ==== The development of bio-based packaging has been an important goal for packaging producers. On June 3, 2015, Coca-Cola presented their version of a 100% recyclable [[Polyethylene terephthalate|PET]] bottle, called PlantBottle™ which in fact was the first of its kind.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Coca-Cola Introduced World’s First 100% Biobased PET Bottle|url = http://www.bioplasticsmagazine.com/en/news/meldungen/20150604_Coca-Cola.php|website = www.bioplasticsmagazine.com|accessdate = 2015-11-30}}</ref> In contrast to usual PET, PlantBottle™ does not rely on fossil-based material. For the production of its bottle, Coca-Cola is supplied by the Brazilian petrochemical and biopolymers company [[Braskem]], who produce [[polyethylene]] that is based in its entirety on sugarcane ethanol.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Coca-Cola expands PlantBottle reach, launches 100% plant-based HDPE {{!}} Packaging World|url = http://www.packworld.com/sustainability/strategy/coca-cola-expands-plantbottle-reach-launches-100-plant-based-hdpe|website = www.packworld.com|accessdate = 2015-11-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = I'm green™ Polyethylene - Braskem|url = http://www.braskem.com/site.aspx/Im-greenTM-Polyethylene|website = www.braskem.com|accessdate = 2015-11-30}}</ref> Furthermore, [[Tetra Pak]] announced the launch of a 100% renewable package for their dairy products.<ref name=":1">{{Cite web|title = Tetra Pak Launches 100% Renewable Package Globally · Environmental Leader · Environmental Management News|url = http://www.environmentalleader.com/2015/11/16/tetra-pak-launches-100-renewable-package-globally/|website = www.environmentalleader.com|accessdate = 2015-11-30}}</ref> This innovative packaging concept won Tetra Pak the "Best carton or pouch" and "Best manufacturing or processing innovation" prizes at the World Beverage Innovation Awards 2015 as well as a Gold Award at the Pro2Pac Excellence Awards in the UK for "being the world’s first carton made entirely from plant-based, renewable packaging materials".<ref>{{Cite web|title = Tetra Pak Launches 100% Renewable Package Globally · Environmental Leader · Environmental Management News|url = http://www.environmentalleader.com/2015/11/16/tetra-pak-launches-100-renewable-package-globally/|website = www.environmentalleader.com|accessdate = 2015-12-01|date = 2015-11-16|first = Karen|last = Henry}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Interview: Tetra Pak state award win is a ‘recognition of efforts’|url = http://www.foodbev.com/news/interview-tetra-pak-state-award-win-is-a-recognition-of-efforts/|website = FoodBev|accessdate = 2015-11-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Winners and finalists of the World Beverage Innovation Awards 2015 announced|url = http://www.foodbev.com/news/winners-and-finalists-of-the-world-beverage-innovation-awards-2015-announced/|website = FoodBev|accessdate = 2015-11-30}}</ref> For the production of its sustainable packaging solution Tetra Pak also uses sugar cane [[bioplastic]]s provided by Braskem.<ref name=":1" />
The Brazilian sugarcane industry is a promising market as well as a future indispensable part of the country's packaging market. Sugarcane ethanol is produced in areas that are located in at least 2000&nbsp;km distance from the Amazon rainforest, that is, in the [[Northeast Region, Brazil|Northeast]] coastal regions as well as in the [[Southeast Region, Brazil|Southeast]], with 60% of the production taking place in the [[São Paulo (state)|State of São Paulo]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = Brazilian Sugarcane Industry|url = http://thebrazilbusiness.com/article/brazilian-sugarcane-industry|website = The Brazil Business|accessdate = 2015-11-30|date = 2015-01-22|last = Verotti Farah|first = Ana Gabriela}}</ref>
=== Recycling in Brazil === {{Main article|Recycling in Brazil}} [[File:RecyclingBrazil.png|thumb|390x390px|Recycling activity in Brazil in 2012: percentage of recycled material per material. Data according to ''ABAL'', ''ABIPET'', ''ABRAVIDRO'', ''ABPO'', ''ABTCP'', ''ABRE'', and ''ABIPLAST''.<ref>The Braziian Associations of the aluminum, PET, glass, cardboard, paper, packaging and plastics industry, respectively.</ref>]] Compared to developed OECD states, Brazil has a fairly low total recycling rate, being at 2% of created waste.<ref name=":5">{{Cite web|title = Recycling of Waste in Brazil|url = http://thebrazilbusiness.com/article/recycling-of-waste-in-brazil|website = The Brazil Business|accessdate = 2015-12-02|last = Nóvais|first = Andrea|date = 2015-05-13}}</ref> As in 2012 merely 14% of municipalities provided selective waste collection - with 86% of these municipalities located in either the [[South Region, Brazil|South]] or Southeastern region - the country relies heavily on [[:pt:Catador de material reciclável|waste pickers]].<ref>{{Cite book|title = CEMPRE Review 2013|publisher = Compromisso Empresarial de Recliclagem (CEMPRE)|year = 2013|isbn = |location = |pages = 21|language = Portuguese}}</ref> Additionally to that, only 64% of the population has access to regular garbage collection.<ref name=":5" /> Yet, the situation is improving since the absolute number of municipalities offering selective collection rose from 443 in 2010 to 766 in 2012.<ref>{{Cite book|title = CEMPRE Review 2013|publisher = CEMPRE|year = 2013|isbn = |location = |pages = 22}}</ref> [[File:RecyclingPET.png|390x390px|Destinations of recycled PET in Brazil in 2012. Data according to ''ABIPET'' and ''CEMPRE''.<ref>CEMPRE is a non-profit organization that promotes recycling to the Brazilian industry.</ref> |thumb]] Despite its low overall recycling rate, Brazil is the world leader in recycling aluminum. Having set a record recycling rate of 98,4% of aluminum, the country was able to top its record 97,1% from 2013 by another 1,3%.<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://latino.foxnews.com/latino/news/2015/11/10/brazil-breaks-aluminum-recycling-record/|title = Brazil breaks aluminum recycling record|last = Cleyton|first = Vilarino|date = 2015-11-10|work = Fox News Latino|access-date = 2015-12-02|via = |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151211035948/http://latino.foxnews.com/latino/news/2015/11/10/brazil-breaks-aluminum-recycling-record/#|archive-date = 2015-12-11|dead-url = yes|df = }}</ref> The main reason for the extreme aluminum recycling rate are the rising energy costs - which will continue to rise given the increasing hydropower prices caused by the [[2015 Brazilian drought|2015 drought]] - and consequently, the high expenses that are associated with the production of new aluminum. As between March 2014 and March 2015 the cost of energy rose by 60% and since recycling aluminum requires 95% less energy than producing new material, the recycling rates have kept rising while smelter plants have been shutting down production.<ref>{{Cite news|title = UPDATE 1-Alcoa's Brazil aluminum smelter latest victim of high costs|url = https://www.reuters.com/article/2015/03/30/alcoa-capacity-idUSL3N0WW4XZ20150330|newspaper = Reuters|date = 2015-03-30|access-date = 2015-12-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = RECICLAR Materiais Recicláveis|url = http://www.reciclarbrasil.com.br/meioambiente.asp|website = www.reciclarbrasil.com.br|accessdate = 2015-12-02|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151224192503/http://www.reciclarbrasil.com.br/meioambiente.asp#|archive-date = 2015-12-24|dead-url = yes|df = }}</ref> PET is the second most recycled packaging material in Brazil with 54% of PET having been recycled in 2014. However, due to lower production costs this rate is yet much smaller than the percentage of recycled aluminum. Given its very low production costs as well as the more expensive processes needed to recycle the material, plastics exhibit the lowest recycling rate among the most common packaging materials. The Brazilian beauty care and cosmetics brand Sejaa serves as an example for products that use recycled packaging. Sejaa, which was launched by Brazilian fashion model [[Gisele Bündchen]] uses fibers consisting to 100% of recycled post-consumer waste paper and is Forest Stewardship certified.<ref>{{Cite book|title = Brasil PackTrends 2020|last = Sarantópoulos|publisher = ITAL|year = 2012|isbn = |location = |pages = 136|display-authors=etal}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url = http://shopsejaa.com/standard.php|title = Seeja standard|date = |accessdate = 2015-12-03|website = |publisher = |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151210214907/http://shopsejaa.com/standard.php#|archive-date = 2015-12-10|dead-url = yes|df = }}</ref> Another example is Brazilian pulp and paper manufacturer [[Suzano Papel e Celulose|Suzano]], which since 2012 produces paperboard made from Post consumer resin (PCR) by extracting fibers from long life packaging<ref>Long life packaging is packaging consisting of multiple layers that make the packaging more durable. A typical example of long life packaging is a milk carton.</ref> such as milk cartons.<ref>{{Cite book|title = CEMPRE Review 2013|publisher = CEMPRE|year = 2013|isbn = |location = |pages = 29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Suzano lança papel cartão feito com aparas recicladas {{!}} VEJA.com|url = http://veja.abril.com.br/noticia/economia/suzano-lanca-papel-cartao-feito-com-aparas-recicladas/|website = VEJA.com|publisher = VEJA|accessdate = 2015-12-03}}</ref>
In 2012, more than one third of recycled PET was used as polyesters for the textile industry. Roughly one quarter of recycled PET was processed to alkyds, that is, synthetic resins which are mostly used as varnish, while packaging accounted for 18% of recycled PET.
