{{More citations needed|date=July 2017}}
'''Fire polishing''', also known as '''flame polishing''', is a method of [[polishing]] a material, usually [[glass]] or [[thermoplastic]]s, by exposing it to a [[flame]] or heat.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=oe5YJmRmxQMC&pg=PA199&dq=Flame+polishing+used+on+glass|title=Plastics Materials and Processes: A Concise Encyclopedia|last=Harper|first=Charles A.|last2=Petrie|first2=Edward M.|date=2003-10-10|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=9780471459200|language=en}}</ref> When the surface of the material briefly melts, [[surface tension]] smooths the surface. Operator skill is critical with this method. When done properly, flame plastic polishing produces the clearest finish, especially when polishing [[acrylic resin|acrylic]]. This method is most applicable to flat external surfaces. Flame polishing is frequently used in acrylic plastic fabrication because of its high speed compared to abrasive methods. In this application, an [[oxyhydrogen torch]] is typically used, one reason being that the flame chemistry is unlikely to contaminate the plastic.

Flame polishing is essential to creation of the [[Pasteur pipette|glass pipettes]] used for the [[patch clamp]] technique of [[voltage clamp]]ing.

==See also==
*[[Fire hardening]], also known as "fire polishing", a primitive process for hardening wood

